<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-exponential-functions">
  <title>Exponential functions</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use slope fields and numerical steps to explore solution behavior.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Model growth and decay using proportional rates of change.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Recognize exponential curves as natural solutions to proportional-rate equations.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Population growth:
        <me>
          \dv{y}{t}=ky
        </me>
        How can we figure out which function satisfies this relationship?
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Introduce slope fields and Euler's method
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        We find that the solution curves are always exponential curves. When <m>k=1</m>, we have <m>\DS\dv{y}{t}=y</m>, so we'll call the solution for which <m>y(0)=1</m> the <term>exponential function</term> and label it <m>y=\exp(t)</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        By properties of derivatives, we know that the solution of <m>\DS\dv{y}{t}=y</m> with <m>y(0)=c</m> must be <m>y=c\exp(t)</m>. In particular, the solution of <m>\DS\dv{y}{t}=y</m> with <m>y(0)=\exp(a)</m> must be <m>y=\exp(a)\exp(t)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        However, using the Chain Rule, we can also show that <m>y=\exp(a+t)</m> is a solution of <m>\DS\dv{y}{t}=y</m> with <m>y(0)=\exp(a)</m>, since
        <me>
          \dv{t}\exp(a+t) = \exp(a+t)\cdot\dv{t}(a+t) = \exp(a+t)\cdot 1 = \exp(a+t)
        </me>.
        Since the solution to a linear differential equation is unique, we must have <m>\exp(a+t)=\exp(a)\exp(t)</m>. This is exactly the behavior we expect from exponents, since <m>b^{x+y}=b^xb^y</m> for any base <m>b\gt 0</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        It can be shown numerically that
        <me>
          \exp(1)=2.718281828459045235\cdots=\ee
        </me>,
        so instead of <m>\exp(t)</m>, we can write <m>\ee^t</m>, and hence we have
        <me>
          \ee^{a+t}=\ee^a\ee^t
        </me>
        as expected.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        We can write this as an integral as well:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\int \ee^x\dd{x} \amp = \ee^x+C</mrow>
      </md>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Overall, the solution to the original differential equation <m>\DS\dv{y}{t}=ky</m> is
        <me>
          y=y_{0}\ee^{kt}
        </me>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        When <m>k\gt 0</m>, we get exponential growth.
      </p>
      <p>
        When <m>k\lt 0</m>, we get exponential decay.
      </p>
    </li>

    
  </ul>
</section>
